---
source: benches/baselines/hardware_classes.toml, scripts/sync_perf_table.sh, README.md
assertion: performance baselines are pinned to declared hardware classes before README sync
surface: perf_hardware_manifest
bead: bd-3usjw.27
contracts:
  - benches/baselines/hardware_classes.toml declares named hardware classes
  - mac-m3-pro is the canonical README baseline class
  - CI and stress hardware classes are non-canonical and cannot silently replace Mac baseline numbers
  - scripts/sync_perf_table.sh accepts ee.perf.v1 and ee.perf.baseline.v1 artifacts
  - sync_perf_table rejects artifacts that are not pinned to a declared hardware class
  - README performance table shows the hardware class for every row
evidence:
  - benches/baselines/hardware_classes.toml
  - scripts/sync_perf_table.sh
  - README.md performance section
  - tests/readme_perf_sync.rs
static_checks:
  - bash -n scripts/sync_perf_table.sh
  - scripts/sync_perf_table.sh --input benches/baselines/perf_v0_2.json --readme README.md --check
  - unpinned perf artifact exits non-zero before README sync
residual_risk:
  - benchmark freshness is enforced by the perf-sync tests and future hardware-class benchmark artifacts
